<subSubSection id="FF989F6E001737EA4037EEA082263CBC" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="513C34D580E45A691E5BCB4B72F837B8" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="62AB53E505554E24F6FD48E59FD835CC" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
In much of its range this species is easily recognised by its creamy-white flowers arranged in subumbellate cymes. However it can only be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="34E8E425156FD2E8F6E4C1960E85C261" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="reticulata">
<emphasis id="03E5485B0D5334249081861C9FEF2654" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea reticulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the larger sepals and corolla and some specimens can be difficult to assign, particularly from the Brasilia area. There is a case, therefore, for treating these two species as subspecies but we are reluctant to make this decision. Although 
<taxonomicName id="C7105F9CFD1765F5E37ED6C9FD54E19F" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="reticulata">
<emphasis id="86970B93BE2D3427A75F18EE0AD40D21" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. reticulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is always glabrous or minutely scabridulous-puberulent, the leaves of 
<taxonomicName id="9CDF7F6F11F4FB629934AD858B4AED14" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="saopaulista">
<emphasis id="560B3AB3682D5398C47E7E9915B4591F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. saopaulista</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are commonly densely pubescent or even tomentose, a state never seen in 
<taxonomicName id="AF06C1BA8E9993FEC0DE33F6716EAEA0" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="reticulata">
<emphasis id="5F7BCDEB94D6412830AF6040EE25D9F2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. reticulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and mere size is not, therefore, the only distinguishing feature between the two species.
</paragraph>
